related_questions.question: How much do you make in the National Guard?
related_questions.snippet: An E-1 with more than four months of service who's called up to active duty makes a base pay of $1,638 a month. As an E-2, you'll make $61 per drill and a base pay of $1,836 a month if you're called up to active duty.Jul 1, 2018

related_questions.question: What does the National Guard do exactly?
related_questions.snippet: The Army National Guard is community-based and reports to the governor of its respective state unless called to protect U.S. domestic interests in times of conflict or natural disaster. They may also be deployed internationally alongside full-time service members when necessary.
related_questions.title: Army National Guard — Today's Military

related_questions.question: Does the National Guard go to war?
related_questions.snippet: The National Guard however, is controlled by their respective state. The Army Reserves go to war overseas, whereas the National Guard is meant to stay in the United States for support. Of all the soldiers serving in Iraq, none affect their home communities as much as those serving in the Army National Guard.
